---
import Heading from "@components/Heading.astro";
import HeadingLarge from "@components/HeadingLarge.astro";
import Text from "@components/Text.astro";
import View from "@components/View.astro";
import Group from "@components/Group.astro";
import { Layout } from "@layouts";
import Image from "@components/Image.astro";

export const prerender = true;
---

<Layout
  title="Rainforest | Work | Jonathon Toon | Software Designer & Product Leader"
  description="Jonathon Toon is a versatile software designer and product leader based in Aotearoa New Zealand."
  keywords="design, software, product, fractional, leadership, new zealand, aotearoa, technology, typescript, start ups, engineering, mentorship, coaching, adplist"
  twitterHandle="@jonathontoon"
  canonicalUrl="https://www.jonathontoon.com/"
  ogImage="/images/og-image.png"
>
  <Group>
    <HeadingLarge class="px-2">Rainforest QA</HeadingLarge>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Rainforest QA builds browser-based developer tools that help teams ship
      quickly with confidence, by blending no-code test authoring with
      AI-powered automation.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      I joined as the first designer after a major reorganization, a pivot from
      enterprise sales to a product-led growth focus. This transition required a
      lean structure without dedicated Product Managers, where designers were
      empowered to drive both strategy and execution.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      During this time I also stepped into my first leadership role as Director
      of Design. Guiding a team of three designers and establishing a culture
      where design wasn't just about delivery, but central to defining the
      product itself.
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <View class="px-2">
      <View class="h-px w-full bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-700" />
    </View>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Heading class="px-2">Customer Discovery</Heading>
    <Text class="px-2">
      After joining, I noticed several recent releases in the product hadn't
      landed as expected. While we built technically impressive features, they
      didn't meet customer quality standards. This was an indicator that we
      weren't close enough to understanding their core needs.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      I flagged this to the founders, proposing a short pause on further product
      work to conduct some customer discovery. The intent wasn't to stop all
      work, but to reorient focus and recalibrate our intuition.
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Image
      src="/images/work/rainforest-qa-customer-research-1.png"
      alt="Rainforest QA wordmark and logomark refreshed for the product-led brand."
      width={3840}
      height={2560}
      class="w-full rounded-xl bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-800"
      lightbox={true}
    />
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Partnering with the CTO and a Customer Success Manager, we interviewed
      three key cohorts over two weeks: potential customers, active users, and
      those who had churned.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      While doing so, we examined the opinions of critical areas: the marketing
      website (our primary growth engine) and the test authoring experience (the
      product’s core value).
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Image
      src="/images/work/rainforest-qa-customer-research-2.png"
      alt="Rainforest QA wordmark and logomark refreshed for the product-led brand."
      width={3840}
      height={2560}
      class="w-full rounded-xl bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-800"
      lightbox={true}
    />
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Research from 30 interviews uncovered a wealth of insights, from confusing
      user flows to critical bugs. While painful to hear, the feedback reignited
      the team's passion for building a product we had strong conviction for.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      It was agreed that the feedback was significant enough to reshape our
      roadmap, shifting focus for the next six months to address the most major
      findings.
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <View class="px-2">
      <View class="h-px w-full bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-700" />
    </View>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Heading class="px-2">Test Authoring</Heading>
    <Text class="px-2">
      To serve teams without dedicated QA engineers, we needed a faster path
      from idea to executable test. Alongside our engineers the design team led
      a holistic rethink which resulted in 12 months of small iterative
      projects.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      The goal was to simplify the test writing experience to help new users see
      value sooner, while helping everyday customers write tests that were
      significantly more resilient to failure.
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Image
      src="/images/work/rainforest-qa-test-creation.png"
      alt="Rainforest QA no-code test authoring interface with reusable steps."
      width={3840}
      height={2560}
      class="w-full rounded-xl bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-800"
      lightbox={true}
    />
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Text class="px-2">
      We started by rethinking the core interaction model. Using the project's
      natural language interface, we established a clear taxonomy of "actions" a
      user could instruct the browser to take.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      This enabled users to write tests that read like user stories, directly in
      a live browser. It lowered the barrier to entry, ensuring that anyone,
      even non-technical staff, could understand and contribute to the test
      suite.
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Image
      src="/images/work/rainforest-qa-test-authoring.png"
      alt="Rainforest QA no-code test authoring interface with reusable steps."
      width={3840}
      height={2560}
      class="w-full rounded-xl bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-800"
      lightbox={true}
    />
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Text class="px-2">
      To prevent duplication, we introduced a modular component system. Users
      could group frequent actions, such as "Login" or "Checkout", into reusable
      steps. This created a shared library across teams, meaning a single update
      to one test would instantly propagate to every other test, drastically
      reducing maintenance overhead.
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Image
      src="/images/work/rainforest-qa-test-run.png"
      alt="Rainforest QA no-code test authoring interface with reusable steps."
      width={3840}
      height={2560}
      class="w-full rounded-xl bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-800"
      lightbox={true}
    />
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Lastly, we clarified the execution process. It was critical users
      understood how they were running a test, whether via our automated AI
      agents or using a real person from our crowdsourced tester pool.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      We surfaced these modes alongside their respective costs, allowing teams
      to make informed decisions regarding speed, human insight, and budget.
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Heading class="px-2">Idea Evaluation</Heading>
    <Text class="px-2">
      During my time at the company, ideas would always arrive rapidly from
      every direction, including leadership, engineering, sales, and support.
      Without a structured evaluation process, the team frequently paused work
      to debate new possibilities, losing focus on goals.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      To manage this, I worked with the Director of Engineering to establish an
      evaluation framework adapted from Basecamp’s “Shape Up”. This introduced a
      rubric a team would use before committing to any non-critical work.
    </Text>
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Image
      src="/images/work/rainforest-qa-shaping-1.png"
      alt="Rainforest QA no-code test authoring interface with reusable steps."
      width={3840}
      height={2560}
      class="w-full rounded-xl bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-800"
      lightbox={true}
    />
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Image
      src="/images/work/rainforest-qa-shaping-2.png"
      alt="Rainforest QA no-code test authoring interface with reusable steps."
      width={3840}
      height={2560}
      class="w-full rounded-xl bg-stone-200 dark:bg-stone-800"
      lightbox={true}
    />
  </Group>
  <Group>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Its purpose was to require anyone proposing an idea to answer critical
      questions about customer impact, business value, and more importantly
      success criteria.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      Crucially, it gave leadership transparency into the goals of committed
      work, allowing them to contribute insights or veto initiatives that
      strayed from the vision.
    </Text>
    <Text class="px-2">
      In an organization without a dedicated product management function, this
      shared context was vital. It distributed product thinking across the
      company, ensuring everyone considered the “why” behind their work, not
      just the “how.”
    </Text>
  </Group>
